05246nam a22007935i 9780814739693DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t19961996nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147396937 a10.18574/97808147396932doi  a(DE-B1597)550542  a(OCoLC)1163878754  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHB501b.S5896 1996eb 7aBUS0350002bisacsh04a330.12/22201 aSilk, Leonard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking Capitalism Work :bAll Makes, All Models /cLeonard Silk, Mark Silk. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1996] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tONE. The March of Capitalism -- tTWO. The Challenge of Slow Growth -- tTHREE. American Contracts -- tFOUR. The Soviet Bloc in Transition -- tFIVE. The Chinese Puzzle -- tSIX. Japan at the Crossroads -- tSEVEN. Whither Northern Europe? -- tEIGHT. Military Spending as Industrial Policy -- tNINE. The Future of Capitalism -- tEpilogue: The (Political) Economy of Capitalism -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1995, Republicans came to power in the United States with an ambitious program proposing to embrace a degree of laissez- faire economics unknown for generations anywhere in the industrialized world. Simultaneously, politicians, entrepreneurs, and economists championed the new bastions of unregulated capitalism that sprung up in such unfamiliar precincts as Beijing and Moscow. Yet to date many free-market economic policies, be it in Prague or here in America, have not lived up to their initial promises. In fact, it has become a common joke in Russia that capitalism has succeeded in making communism look good, a feat unaccomplished by the Kremlin in its 70 year reign. In Making Capitalism Work, Leonard and Mark Silk analyze the failures and successes of capitalism as seen most recently in the former Soviet Bloc, Japan, China, the European Community and the United States. While recognizing that capitalism has been successful in a number of countries, the authors point out that overly simplistic policies advocating an unfettered capitalism ignore too large a range of issues central to the formation of any moral economic system. Viewing capitalism as simply one of a number of economic systems, Leonard and Mark Silk address such issues as the obligation of the rich to the poor, the responsibility of the state to insulate its citizens from market fluctuations, the responsibility of present generations to provide for future ones, and whether economic systems can set the proper extent and limits of individual rights and freedoms. An important, concise, thought-provoking book this is the last book Leonard Silk wrote before his death late last year and has been completed here by his son, Mark.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCapitalism. 0aEconomic policy. 0aPost-communism. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / International / General.2bisacsh1 aHeilbroner, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeone, Richard C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPontusson, Jonas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilk, Leonard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilk, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSilk, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWasow, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311071692440uh